At midnight, my phone buzzed. “Hope to see you,” he wrote. I lay on my bed, staring at the ceiling fan’s slow, hypnotic spin, debating whether my friendship was worth one more hour awake. Outside, I could hear the distant thump of music from the warehouse district. I rolled to my feet. 

The night air slapped me awake as I biked across town. When I arrived, Jasper was just stepping onto the stage. He saw me, grinned, and started playing a song he’d written for me—something soft and hopeful. I melted into the crowd, exhaustion forgotten, grateful for a world that sometimes rewarded effort with moments like this.
